{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500420"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:13:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:13:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1642"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1642"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.12,0.3,0.15,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1642"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68619"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1642"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1642"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54076"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"875"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"2418"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8626"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8678"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15130"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15337"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18692"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37029"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68619"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic to review a gastrointestinal concern he has had for the last twelve months. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a non-smoker and drinks alcohol occasionally. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. A fluoroscopic swallow study is performed and one of the sequences is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would have been the most likely symptom at this patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Halitosis","Nocturnal cough","Dysphagia","Heartburn","Vomiting"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe fluoroscopic swallow study shows a large outpouching from the distal oesophagus, with contrast pooling in the cavity and an air-fluid level visible. This is characteristic of an epiphrenic diverticulum, which is an oesophageal diverticulum located immediately above the lower oesophageal sphincter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDysphagia\u003C/strong\u003E (difficulty swallowing) is by far the most common presenting symptom of an epiphrenic diverticulum. This typically affects solids more than liquids and is often related to an underlying oesophageal motility disorder associated with the diverticulum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeartburn\u003C/strong\u003E is a recognised symptom that can be seen in cases of oesophageal diverticulum, but is more likely to be related to gastro-oesophageal reflux, than regurgitation of the contents of the diverticulum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHalitosis\u003C/strong\u003E (bad breath) can be a symptom of oesophageal diverticula due to food retention and bacterial overgrowth in the pouch, but it is not typically the primary presenting complaint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENocturnal cough\u003C/strong\u003E may occur in some patients with oesophageal diverticula due to aspiration of retained food or secretions, particularly when lying down. However, this is not as common as dysphagia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVomiting\u003C/strong\u003E is not a typical presenting symptom of epiphrenic diverticula. While patients may experience regurgitation, true vomiting is uncommon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEpiphrenic diverticula can be either traction or pulsion in origin, with pulsion diverticula being more common. They are often associated with underlying oesophageal motility disorders. Other potential symptoms include chest pain and aspiration. Management depends on the severity of symptoms and may include observation, lifestyle modifications, or surgical intervention in severe cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Epiphrenic diverticulum most commonly presents with dysphagia.","Epiphrenic diverticula are located immediately above the lower oesophageal sphincter and are usually associated with an underlying oesophageal motility disorder.","Fluoroscopic swallow studies can effectively diagnose oesophageal diverticula."],"references":["Bennett B, Akhondi H. Epiphrenic Diverticula. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2022 Jul 4]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559110/","Tedesco P, Fisichella PM, Way LW, Patti MG. Cause and treatment of epiphrenic diverticula. The American Journal of Surgery. 2005;190(6):902-5. Available at: https://www.americanjournalofsurgery.com/article/S0002-9610(05)00714-2/abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54076"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1642"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19682"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19682"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dc5d5181-e9b6-4fd6-9346-4ce32d10fd3c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dc5d5181-e9b6-4fd6-9346-4ce32d10fd3c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":426,"height":500}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54076"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-